com.nokia.maps.map

Class MapDisplay

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.nokia.maps.map.MapDisplay

  • public abstract class MapDisplay
extends java.lang.Object
    This class displays a portion of a geographical map, allowing multiple optional layers (MapContainers) and MapObjects to be added to it. To instantiate MapDisplay correctly please use the MapFactory.createMapDisplay method.

    A map resolution enumeration used to create the MapDisplay. Resolution defines size of the tile images used to compile map image.

    Supported resolutions are

    • MAP_RESOLUTION_128_x_128
    • MAP_RESOLUTION_256_x_256
    • MAP_RESOLUTION_AUTO
    Auto resolution may use either 128x128 or 256x256 map tiles depending on the geometry of the device. Should size of the device exceed 65536 pixels, then tiles of 256 by 256 pixels are used, otherwise 128 by 128 pixel tiles is used. The default setting is MAP_RESOLUTION_AUTO

    The MapDisplay is container for MapObjects which are visual objects shown on top of the map. MapObjects can be grouped using the MapContainer. For more information how objects are placed see MapObject and MapContainer documentation.

      • drag

        public abstract void drag(Point start,
        Point end)
        This method drags the map by the delta defined by start and end point, just like pan(com.nokia.maps.map.Point, com.nokia.maps.map.Point), except that no new MapData is downloaded by this method. Primarily intended for use for while handling javax.microedition.lcdui.Canvas#pointerDragged() events.
        Parameters:
        start - An object containing the x and y pixels of the start position of the panning
        end - An object containing the x and y pixels of the end position of the panning action

      • reconnect

        public abstract void reconnect()
        This method forces the tile providers to restart. It is usually called if an error has occurred. For instance, if the cause of a MapListener#onMapUpdateError() is due to an IOException, the user can be prompted to reconnect. This method should be called on the reconnect as it attempts to reconnect to the providers.

      • setCache

        public abstract void setCache(java.lang.String uri,
            int maxNumberOfObjects,
            int percentFree)
                       throws java.io.IOException
        This method enables persistent caching. This method depends on an implementation of JSR075 being present. The uri can be either a full file:/// location describing the root of the cache storage, or it can be a relative path (without a leading '/') or null. If the uri is null or a relative path then the default location is on a the last writable volume that is found using FileSystemRegistry.listRoots(). In the case where the uri is null, the default directory is file:///<root>/cache. The percentFree amount should be between 10 and 90. This is the amount of free space to try and maintain on the volume which contains the cache. Should this threshold be exceeded for instance if the free space on the volume falls to 30 percent and the threshold was set to 30 then the cache attempts to increase the free space by removing cached objects. This method doesn't block, and the warning received about running this method in a separate thread may be safely ignored.
        Parameters:
        uri - the absolute or relative folder to store cache files or null
        maxNumberOfObjects - the maximum number of objects that the cache stores
        percentFree - the minimum percentage of free space to try maintain on the volume
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - if the cache cannot be set.
